[Student "S"]
{North is to play 4\S. East leads the \HA, then the \HK, then \H10.

Losers:   \S=0  \H=2  \D=0  \C=2  Total = 4

The 2 \Hs are already lost, so you put your mind to the 2 \Cs. If the suit splits 3-3 the problem goes away, but a 4-2 split is more likely. So you should plan to ruff the fourth \C in dummy.   

Ruff the third \H. Then play \C A K 3. East discards a \H on the third \C which West wins. West will probably return his last \C at this point, hoping East can ruff higher than dummy's \S9. But he cannot, so you ruff in dummy, pull trumps and claim the rest.

This was a good plan, pretty much guaranteed to work unless the \Cs split 5-1 so that somebody ruffed on of your \C winners.

But, it was a good plan because dummy held the \S9. Keep that in mind when you look at Deal 15.}
[Play "W"]HA

